# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: custom-resource-definitions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] This page shows how to install a custom resource into the Kubernetes API by creating a CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] You need to have a Kubernetes cluster, and the kubectl command-line tool must be configured to communicate with your cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] It is recommended to run this tutorial on a cluster with at least two nodes that are not acting as control plane hosts.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Your Kubernetes server must be at or later than version 1.16.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] To check the version, enter `kubectl version`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] If you are using an older version of Kubernetes that is still supported, switch to the documentation for that version to see advice that is relevant for your cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] When you create a new CustomResourceDefinition (CRD), the Kubernetes API Server creates a new RESTful resource path for each version you specify.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] The custom resource created from a CRD object can be either namespaced or cluster-scoped, as specified in the CRD's `spec.scope` field.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] As with existing built-in objects, deleting a namespace deletes all custom objects in that namespace.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] CustomResourceDefinitions themselves are non-namespaced and are available to all namespaces.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] This endpoint URL can then be used to create and manage custom objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] The `kind` of these objects will be `CronTab` from the spec of the CustomResourceDefinition object you created above.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] It might take a few seconds for the endpoint to be created.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] You can watch the `Established` condition of your CustomResourceDefinition to be true or watch the discovery information of the API server for your resource to show up.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] After the CustomResourceDefinition object has been created, you can create custom objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Custom objects can contain custom fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] These fields can contain arbitrary JSON.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] In the following example, the `cronSpec` and `image` custom fields are set in a custom object of kind `CronTab`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] The kind `CronTab` comes from the spec of the CustomResourceDefinition object you created above.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] You can then manage your CronTab objects using kubectl.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Resource names are not case-sensitive when using kubectl, and you can use either the singular or plural forms defined in the CRD, as well as any short names.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] When you delete a CustomResourceDefinition, the server will uninstall the RESTful API endpoint and delete all custom objects stored in it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] If you later recreate the same CustomResourceDefinition, it will start out empty.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] CustomResources store structured data in custom fields (alongside the built-in fields `apiVersion`, `kind` and `metadata`, which the API server validates implicitly).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] With OpenAPI v3.0 validation a schema can be specified, which is validated during creation and updates, compare below for details and limits of such a schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] With `apiextensions.k8s.io/v1` the definition of a structural schema is mandatory for CustomResourceDefinitions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] In the beta version of CustomResourceDefinition, the structural schema was optional.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] 2. for each field in an object and each item in an array which is specified within any of `allOf`, `anyOf`, `oneOf` or `not`, the schema also specifies the field/item outside of those logical junctors (compare example 1 and 2).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] 3. does not set `description`, `type`, `default`, `additionalProperties`, `nullable` within an `allOf`, `anyOf`, `oneOf` or `not`, with the exception of the two pattern for `x-kubernetes-int-or-string: true` (see below).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] 4. if `metadata` is specified, then only restrictions on `metadata.name` and `metadata.generateName` are allowed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Violations of the structural schema rules are reported in the `NonStructural` condition in the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] CustomResourceDefinitions store validated resource data in the cluster's persistence store, etcd.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] As with native Kubernetes resources such as ConfigMap, if you specify a field that the API server does not recognize, the unknown field is *pruned* (removed) before being persisted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] CRDs converted from `apiextensions.k8s.io/v1beta1` to `apiextensions.k8s.io/v1` might lack structural schemas, and `spec.preserveUnknownFields` might be `true`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Set `spec.preserveUnknownFields` to `false`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Notice that the field `someRandomField` was pruned.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] This example turned off client-side validation to demonstrate the API server's behavior, by adding the `--validate=false` command line option.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Because the OpenAPI validation schemas are also published to clients, `kubectl` also checks for unknown fields and rejects those objects well before they would be sent to the API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] By default, all unspecified fields for a custom resource, across all versions, are pruned.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] It is possible though to opt-out of that for specific sub-trees of fields by adding `x-kubernetes-preserve-unknown-fields: true` in the structural OpenAPI v3 validation schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] The field `json` can store any JSON value, without anything being pruned.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] With this, only `object` type values are allowed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] This means that the `something` field in the specified `spec` object is pruned, but everything outside is not.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] With one of those specification, both an integer and a string validate.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] In Validation Schema Publishing, `x-kubernetes-int-or-string: true` is unfolded to one of the two patterns shown above.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] RawExtensions (as in `runtime.RawExtension`) holds complete Kubernetes objects, i.e. with `apiVersion` and `kind` fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] It is possible to specify those embedded objects (both completely without constraints or partially specified) by setting `x-kubernetes-embedded-resource: true`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] Because `x-kubernetes-preserve-unknown-fields: true` is specified alongside, nothing is pruned.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] The use of `x-kubernetes-preserve-unknown-fields: true` is optional though.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] With `x-kubernetes-embedded-resource: true`, the `apiVersion`, `kind` and `metadata` are implicitly specified and validated.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p01] See Custom resource definition versioning for more information about serving multiple versions of your CustomResourceDefinition and migrating your objects from one version to another.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Identifiers of custom finalizers consist of a domain name, a forward slash and the name of the finalizer.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Any controller can add a finalizer to any object's list of finalizers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The first delete request on an object with finalizers sets a value for the `metadata.deletionTimestamp` field but does not delete it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Once this value is set, entries in the `finalizers` list can only be removed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] While any finalizers remain it is also impossible to force the deletion of an object.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] When the `metadata.deletionTimestamp` field is set, controllers watching the object execute any finalizers they handle and remove the finalizer from the list after they are done.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] It is the responsibility of each controller to remove its finalizer from the list.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The value of `metadata.deletionGracePeriodSeconds` controls the interval between polling updates.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Once the list of finalizers is empty, meaning all finalizers have been executed, the resource is deleted by Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Custom resources are validated via OpenAPI v3.0 schemas, by x-kubernetes-validations when the Validation Rules feature is enabled, and you can add additional validation using admission webhooks.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `x-kubernetes-validations` extension can be used to validate custom resources using Common Expression Language (CEL) expressions when the Validation rules feature is enabled and the CustomResourceDefinition schema is a structural schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Refer to the structural schemas section for other restrictions and CustomResourceDefinition features.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The schema is defined in the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] A request to create a custom object of kind CronTab is rejected if there are invalid values in its fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If the fields contain valid values, the object creation request is accepted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If you are using a version of Kubernetes older than v1.30, you need to explicitly enable the `CRDValidationRatcheting` feature gate to use this behavior, which then applies to all CustomResourceDefinitions in your cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Provided you enabled the feature gate, Kubernetes implements *validation ratcheting* for CustomResourceDefinitions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The API server is willing to accept updates to resources that are not valid after the update, provided that each part of the resource that failed to validate was not changed by the update operation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] In other words, any invalid part of the resource that remains invalid must have already been wrong.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] You cannot use this mechanism to update a valid resource so that it becomes invalid.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] This feature allows authors of CRDs to confidently add new validations to the OpenAPIV3 schema under certain conditions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Users can update to the new schema safely without bumping the version of the object or breaking workflows.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] While most validations placed in the OpenAPIV3 schema of a CRD support ratcheting, there are a few exceptions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Validation rules use the Common Expression Language (CEL) to validate custom resource values.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Validation rules are included in CustomResourceDefinition schemas using the `x-kubernetes-validations` extension.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The Rule is scoped to the location of the `x-kubernetes-validations` extension in the schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] And `self` variable in the CEL expression is bound to the scoped value.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] All validation rules are scoped to the current object: no cross-object or stateful validation rules are supported.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] `x-kubernetes-validations` could have multiple rules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `rule` under `x-kubernetes-validations` represents the expression which will be evaluated by CEL.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `message` represents the message displayed when validation fails.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Validation rules are compiled when CRDs are created/updated.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The request of CRDs create/update will fail if compilation of validation rules fail.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Compilation process includes type checking as well.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `apiVersion`, `kind`, `metadata.name` and `metadata.generateName` are always accessible from the root of the object and from any `x-kubernetes-embedded-resource` annotated objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] No other metadata properties are accessible.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Unknown data preserved in custom resources via `x-kubernetes-preserve-unknown-fields` is not accessible in CEL expressions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Note: CEL RESERVED keyword needs to match the exact property name to be escaped (e.g. int in the word sprint would not be escaped).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Equality on arrays with `x-kubernetes-list-type` of `set` or `map` ignores element order, i.e., `[1, 2] == [2, 1]`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] xref: CEL types, OpenAPI types, Kubernetes Structural Schemas.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Similar to the `message` field, which defines the string reported for a validation rule failure, `messageExpression` allows you to use a CEL expression to construct the message string.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] This allows you to insert more descriptive information into the validation failure message.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] `messageExpression` must evaluate a string and may use the same variables that are available to the `rule` field.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Keep in mind that CEL string concatenation (`+` operator) does not auto-cast to string.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If you have a non-string scalar, use the `string(<value>)` function to cast the scalar to a string like shown in the above example.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] `messageExpression` must evaluate to a string, and this is checked while the CRD is being written.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Note that it is possible to set `message` and `messageExpression` on the same rule, and if both are present, `messageExpression` will be used.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] However, if `messageExpression` evaluates to an error, the string defined in `message` will be used instead, and the `messageExpression` error will be logged.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] This fallback will also occur if the CEL expression defined in `messageExpression` generates an empty string, or a string containing line breaks.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If one of the above conditions are met and no `message` has been set, then the default validation failure message will be used instead.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] `messageExpression` is a CEL expression, so the restrictions listed in Resource use by validation functions apply.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If evaluation halts due to resource constraints during `messageExpression` execution, then no further validation rules will be executed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Setting `messageExpression` is optional.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If you want to set a static message, you can supply `message` rather than `messageExpression`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The value of `message` is used as an opaque error string if validation fails.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] You can add a machine-readable validation failure reason within a `validation`, to be returned whenever a request fails this validation rule.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The HTTP status code returned to the caller will match the reason of the first failed validation rule.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The currently supported reasons are: "FieldValueInvalid", "FieldValueForbidden", "FieldValueRequired", "FieldValueDuplicate".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If not set or unknown reasons, default to use "FieldValueInvalid".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] You can specify the field path returned when the validation fails.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] In the example above, the validation checks the value of field `x` should be less than the value of `maxLimit`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If no `fieldPath` specified, when validation fails, the fieldPath would be default to wherever `self` scoped.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] With `fieldPath` specified, the returned error will have `fieldPath` properly refer to the location of field `x`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `fieldPath` value must be a relative JSON path that is scoped to the location of this x-kubernetes-validations extension in the schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Additionally, it should refer to an existing field within the schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] For example when validation checks if a specific attribute `foo` under a map `testMap`, you could set `fieldPath` to `".testMap.foo"` or `.testMap['foo']'`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If the validation requires checking for unique attributes in two lists, the fieldPath can be set to either of the lists.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] For example, it can be set to `.testList1` or `.testList2`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] It supports child operation to refer to an existing field currently.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Refer to JSONPath support in Kubernetes for more info.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `fieldPath` field does not support indexing arrays numerically.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If your cluster does not have CRD validation ratcheting enabled, the CustomResourceDefinition API doesn't include this field, and trying to set it may result in an error.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The `optionalOldSelf` field is a boolean field that alters the behavior of Transition Rules described below.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Normally, a transition rule will not evaluate if `oldSelf` cannot be determined: during object creation or when a new value is introduced in an update.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If `optionalOldSelf` is set to true, then transition rules will always be evaluated and the type of `oldSelf` be changed to a CEL `Optional` type.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] A rule that contains an expression referencing the identifier `oldSelf` is implicitly considered a *transition rule*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Transition rules allow schema authors to prevent certain transitions between two otherwise valid states.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Errors will be generated on CRD writes if a schema node contains a transition rule that can never be applied, e.g.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] "oldSelf cannot be used on the uncorrelatable portion of the schema within *path*".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Transition rules are only allowed on *correlatable portions* of a schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] A portion of the schema is correlatable if all `array` parent schemas are of type `x-kubernetes-list-type=map`; any `set`or `atomic`array parent schemas make it impossible to unambiguously correlate a `self` with `oldSelf`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] When you create or update a CustomResourceDefinition that uses validation rules, the API server checks the likely impact of running those validation rules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If a rule is estimated to be prohibitively expensive to execute, the API server rejects the create or update operation, and returns an error message.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] A similar system is used at runtime that observes the actions the interpreter takes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If the interpreter executes too many instructions, execution of the rule will be halted, and an error will result.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Each CustomResourceDefinition is also allowed a certain amount of resources to finish executing all of its validation rules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If the sum total of its rules are estimated at creation time to go over that limit, then a validation error will also occur.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] You are unlikely to encounter issues with the resource budget for validation if you only specify rules that always take the same amount of time regardless of how large their input is.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] For example, a rule that asserts that `self.foo == 1` does not by itself have any risk of rejection on validation resource budget groups.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] But if `foo` is a string and you define a validation rule `self.foo.contains("someString")`, that rule takes longer to execute depending on how long `foo` is.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Another example would be if `foo` were an array, and you specified a validation rule `self.foo.all(x, x > 5)`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The cost system always assumes the worst-case scenario if a limit on the length of `foo` is not given, and this will happen for anything that can be iterated over (lists, maps, etc.).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Because of this, it is considered best practice to put a limit via `maxItems`, `maxProperties`, and `maxLength` for anything that will be processed in a validation rule in order to prevent validation errors during cost estimation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] The rejection happens because `self.all` implies calling `contains()` on every string in `foo`, which in turn will check the given string to see if it contains `'a string'`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] Without limits, this is a very expensive rule.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p02] If you do not specify any validation limit, the estimated cost of this rule will exceed the per-rule cost limit.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The cost estimation system takes into account how many times the rule will be executed in addition to the estimated cost of the rule itself.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] If a list inside of a list has a validation rule that uses `self.all`, that is significantly more expensive than a non-nested list with the same rule.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] A rule that would have been allowed on a non-nested list might need lower limits set on both nested lists in order to be allowed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] This is because each item of `foo` is itself an array, and each subarray in turn calls `self.all`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Avoid nested lists and maps if possible where validation rules are used.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Defaults applied when reading data from etcd are not automatically written back to etcd.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] An update request via the API is required to persist those defaults back into etcd.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Default values for non-leaf fields must be pruned (with the exception of defaults for `metadata` fields) and must validate against a provided schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] For example in the above example, a default of `{"replicas": "foo", "badger": 1}` for the `spec` field would be invalid, because `badger` is an unknown field, and `replicas` is not a string.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Default values for `metadata` fields of `x-kubernetes-embedded-resources: true` nodes (or parts of a default value covering `metadata`) are not pruned during CustomResourceDefinition creation, but through the pruning step during handling of requests.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Null values for fields that either don't specify the nullable flag, or give it a `false` value, will be pruned before defaulting happens.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] If a default is present, it will be applied.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] When nullable is `true`, null values will be conserved and won't be defaulted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] with `foo` pruned and defaulted because the field is non-nullable, `bar` maintaining the null value due to `nullable: true`, and `baz` pruned because the field is non-nullable and has no default.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] CustomResourceDefinition OpenAPI v3 validation schemas which are structural and enable pruning are published as OpenAPI v3 and OpenAPI v2 from Kubernetes API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] It is recommended to use the OpenAPI v3 document as it is a lossless representation of the CustomResourceDefinition OpenAPI v3 validation schema while OpenAPI v2 represents a lossy conversion.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The kubectl command-line tool consumes the published schema to perform client-side validation (`kubectl create` and `kubectl apply`), schema explanation (`kubectl explain`) on custom resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The published schema can be consumed for other purposes as well, like client generation or documentation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] For compatibility with OpenAPI V2, the OpenAPI v3 validation schema performs a lossy conversion to the OpenAPI v2 schema.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The schema show up in `definitions` and `paths` fields in the OpenAPI v2 spec.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The following modifications are applied during the conversion to keep backwards compatibility with kubectl in previous 1.13 version.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] These modifications prevent kubectl from being over-strict and rejecting valid OpenAPI schemas that it doesn't understand.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The conversion won't modify the validation schema defined in CRD, and therefore won't affect validation in the API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] If `nullable: true` is set, we drop `type`, `nullable`, `items` and `properties` because OpenAPI v2 is not able to express nullable.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] To avoid kubectl to reject good objects, this is necessary.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The kubectl tool relies on server-side output formatting.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Your cluster's API server decides which columns are shown by the `kubectl get` command.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] You can customize these columns for a CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The following example adds the `Spec`, `Replicas`, and `Age` columns.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Create an instance using the `my-crontab.yaml` from the previous section.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] column is implicit and does not need to be defined in the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Each column includes a `priority` field.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Currently, the priority differentiates between columns shown in standard view or wide view (using the `-o wide` flag).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] If the value inside a CustomResource does not match the type specified for the column, the value is omitted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Use CustomResource validation to ensure that the value types are correct.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The column's `format` controls the style used when `kubectl` prints the value.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Field Selectors let clients select custom resources based on the value of one or more resource fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] All custom resources support the `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` field selectors.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Fields declared in a CustomResourceDefinition may also be used with field selectors when included in the `spec.versions[*].selectableFields` field of the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The `spec.versions[*].selectableFields` field of a CustomResourceDefinition may be used to declare which other fields in a custom resource may be used in field selectors with the feature of `CustomResourceFieldSelectors` feature gate (This feature gate is enabled by default since Kubernetes v1.31).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The following example adds the `.spec.color` and `.spec.size` fields as selectable fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Custom resources support `/status` and `/scale` subresources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The status and scale subresources can be optionally enabled by defining them in the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] When the status subresource is enabled, the `/status` subresource for the custom resource is exposed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] When the scale subresource is enabled, the `/scale` subresource for the custom resource is exposed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The `autoscaling/v1.Scale` object is sent as the payload for `/scale`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] To enable the scale subresource, the following fields are defined in the CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] In the following example, both status and scale subresources are enabled.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] A custom resource can be scaled using the `kubectl scale` command.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] You can use a PodDisruptionBudget to protect custom resources that have the scale subresource enabled.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] Categories is a list of grouped resources the custom resource belongs to (eg.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] You can use `kubectl get <category-name>` to list the resources belonging to the category.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resource-definitions-p03] The following example adds `all` in the list of categories in the CustomResourceDefinition and illustrates how to output the custom resource using `kubectl get all`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] A *resource* is an endpoint in the Kubernetes API that stores a collection of API objects of a certain kind; for example, the built-in *pods* resource contains a collection of Pod objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] A *custom resource* is an extension of the Kubernetes API that is not necessarily available in a default Kubernetes installation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] It represents a customization of a particular Kubernetes installation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] However, many core Kubernetes functions are now built using custom resources, making Kubernetes more modular.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Custom resources can appear and disappear in a running cluster through dynamic registration, and cluster admins can update custom resources independently of the cluster itself.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Once a custom resource is installed, users can create and access its objects using kubectl, just as they do for built-in resources like *Pods*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] On their own, custom resources let you store and retrieve structured data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] When you combine a custom resource with a *custom controller*, custom resources provide a true *declarative API*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The Kubernetes declarative API enforces a separation of responsibilities.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] You declare the desired state of your resource.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The Kubernetes controller keeps the current state of Kubernetes objects in sync with your declared desired state.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] This is in contrast to an imperative API, where you *instruct* a server what to do.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] You can deploy and update a custom controller on a running cluster, independently of the cluster's lifecycle.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Custom controllers can work with any kind of resource, but they are especially effective when combined with custom resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The Operator pattern combines custom resources and custom controllers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] You can use custom controllers to encode domain knowledge for specific applications into an extension of the Kubernetes API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] When creating a new API, consider whether to aggregate your API with the Kubernetes cluster APIs or let your API stand alone.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] for sensitive data, which is similar to a ConfigMap but more secure.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Kubernetes provides these two options to meet the needs of different users, so that neither ease of use nor flexibility is compromised.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Aggregated APIs are subordinate API servers that sit behind the primary API server, which acts as a proxy.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] This arrangement is called API Aggregation(AA).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] To users, the Kubernetes API appears extended.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] CRDs allow users to create new types of resources without adding another API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] You do not need to understand API Aggregation to use CRDs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Regardless of how they are installed, the new resources are referred to as Custom Resources to distinguish them from built-in Kubernetes resources (like pods).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Avoid using a Custom Resource as data storage for application, end user, or monitoring data: architecture designs that store application data within the Kubernetes API typically represent a design that is too closely coupled.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Architecturally, cloud native application architectures favor loose coupling between components.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] If part of your workload requires a backing service for its routine operation, run that backing service as a component or consume it as an external service.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] This way, your workload does not rely on the Kubernetes API for its normal operation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The CustomResourceDefinition API resource allows you to define custom resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Defining a CRD object creates a new custom resource with a name and schema that you specify.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The Kubernetes API serves and handles the storage of your custom resource.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The name of the CRD object itself must be a valid DNS subdomain name derived from the defined resource name and its API group; see how to create a CRD for more details.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Further, the name of an object whose kind/resource is defined by a CRD must also be a valid DNS subdomain name.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] This frees you from writing your own API server to handle the custom resource, but the generic nature of the implementation means you have less flexibility than with API server aggregation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Refer to the custom controller example for an example of how to register a new custom resource, work with instances of your new resource type, and use a controller to handle events.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Usually, each resource in the Kubernetes API requires code that handles REST requests and manages persistent storage of objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The main Kubernetes API server handles built-in resources like *pods* and *services*, and can also generically handle custom resources through CRDs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The aggregation layer allows you to provide specialized implementations for your custom resources by writing and deploying your own API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The main API server delegates requests to your API server for the custom resources that you handle, making them available to all of its clients.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Choose the method that best meets your needs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] CRDs are easier to create than Aggregated APIs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Aggregated APIs offer more advanced API features and customization of other features; for example, the storage layer.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] There are several points to be aware of before adding a custom resource to your cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Installing an Aggregated API server always involves running a new Deployment.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Custom resources consume storage space in the same way that ConfigMaps do.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Creating too many custom resources may overload your API server's storage space.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Custom resources are placed into storage based upon the the current storage version of the resource, defined in the CRD spec.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Any update to a custom resource will use the currently defined storage version to store the resource.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] All other versions either need to have all the fields of that version or define conversions to work properly.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Aggregated API servers may use the same storage as the main API server, in which case the same warning applies.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] CRDs always use the same authentication, authorization, and audit logging as the built-in resources of your API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] If you use RBAC for authorization, most RBAC roles will not grant access to the new resources (except the cluster-admin role or any role created with wildcard rules).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] You'll need to explicitly grant access to the new resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] CRDs and Aggregated APIs often come bundled with new role definitions for the types they add.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Aggregated API servers may or may not use the same authentication, authorization, and auditing as the primary API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Kubernetes client libraries can be used to access custom resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] Not all client libraries support custom resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The *Go* and *Python* client libraries do.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/custom-resources] The `spec.versions[*].selectableFields` field of a CustomResourceDefinition may be used to declare which other fields in a custom resource may be used in field selectors.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] An extensible system is one whose internal structure and dataflow are minimally or not affected by new or modified functionality, for example recompiling or changing the original source code might be unnecessary when changing a system’s behavior, either by the creator or other programmers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Because software systems are long lived and will be modified for new features and added functionalities demanded by users, extensibility enables developers to expand or add to the software’s capabilities and facilitates systematic reuse.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Some of its approaches include facilities for allowing users’ own program routines to be inserted and the abilities to define new data types as well as to define new formatting markup tags.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Extensible design in software engineering is to accept that not everything can be designed in advance.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] A light software framework which allows for changes is provided instead.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Small commands are made to prevent losing the element of extensibility, following the principle of separating work elements into comprehensible units, in order to avoid traditional software development issues including low cohesion and high coupling and allow for continued development.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Embracing change is essential to the extensible design, in which additions will be continual.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Each chunk of the system will be workable with any changes, and the idea of change through addition is the center of the whole system design.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Extensible design supports frequent re-prioritization and allows functionality to be implemented in small steps upon request, which are the principles advocated by the Agile methodologies and iterative development.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Extensibility imposes fewer and cleaner dependencies during development, as well as reduced coupling and more cohesive abstractions, plus well defined interfaces.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Fickleness lies at the basis of all software because of human phenomena since software is an "evolving entity" which is developed and maintained by human beings, yielding ongoing system changes in software specification and implementation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Components of a software are often developed and deployed by unrelated parties independently.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Adaptable software components are necessary since components from external vendors are unlikely to fit into a specific deployment scenario off-the-rack, taking third party users other than the manufacturer into consideration.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Many software systems and software product-lines are derived from a base system, which share a common software architecture or sometimes large parts of the functionality and implementation but are possibly equipped with different components that require an extensible base system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Building software systems that are *independently extensible* is an important challenge.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] An *independently extensible* system not only allows two people to independently develop extensions to the system, but also allows the two extensions to be combined without a global integrity check.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] There are three different forms of software extensibility: white-box extensibility, gray-box extensibility, and black-box extensibility, which are based on what artifacts and the way they are changed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Under this form of extensibility, a software system can be extended by modifying the source code, and it is the most flexible and the least restrictive form.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] There are two sub-forms of extensibility, open-box extensibility and glass-box extensibility, depending on how changes are applied.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Changes are performed invasively in open-box extensible systems; i.e. original source code is directly being hacked into.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] It requires available source code and the modification permitted source code license.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Open-box extensibility is most relevant to bug fixing, internal code refactoring, or production of next version of a software product.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Glass-box extensibility (also called architecture driven frameworks) allows a software system to be extended with available source code, but may not allow the code to be modified.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Extensions have to be separated from the original system in a way that the original system is not affected.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] One example of this form of extensibility is object-oriented application frameworks which achieve extensibility typically by using inheritance and dynamic binding.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] In black-box extensibility (also called data-driven frameworks) no details about a system’s implementation are used for implementing deployments or extensions; only interface specifications are provided.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] This type of approach is more limited than the various white-box approaches.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Black-box extensions are typically achieved through system configuration applications or the use of application-specific scripting languages by defining components interfaces.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Gray-box extensibility is a compromise between a pure white-box and a pure black-box approach, which does not rely fully on the exposure of source code.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Programmers could be given the system’s specialization interface which lists all available abstractions for refinement and specifications on how extensions should be developed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Extensibility and reusability have many emphasized properties in common, including low coupling, modularity and high risk elements’ ability to construct for many different software systems, which is motivated by the observation of software systems often sharing common elements.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Reusability together with extensibility allows a technology to be transferred to another project with less development and maintenance time, as well as enhanced reliability and consistency.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Modern operating systems support extensibility through device drivers and loadable kernel modules.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Many modern applications support extensibility through plug-ins, extension languages, applets, etc.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] The trend of increasing extensibility negatively affects software security.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] CGI (Common Gateway Interface) is one of the primary means by which web servers provide extensibility.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/extensibility] Some people see CGI scripts as "an enormous security hole".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:custom-resource-definitions/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
